\f2\b Today is the anniversary of the birth of James Prescott #Joule
\f3\b0  
\fs23\fsmilli11900 \cf4 (
\fs28 \cf2 1818-1889), English {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physicist"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 physicist}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematician}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brewing_(beer)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 brewer}}, born in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salford,_Greater_Manchester"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Salford}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lancashire"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Lancashire}}. Joule studied the nature of #{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 heat}}, and discovered its relationship to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanical_work"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mechanical work}}. This led to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_conservation_of_energy"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 law of conservation of #energy}}, which in turn led to the development of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_law_of_thermodynamics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 first law of #thermodynamics}}. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 SI derived unit}} of energy, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joule"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 joule}}, is named after him.\cb1 \
\cb3 Joule worked with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Thomson,_1st_Baron_Kelvin"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Lord #Kelvin}} to develop an absolute thermodynamic {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperature"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 temperature}} scale, which came to be called the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Kelvin}} scale. Joule also made observations of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetostriction"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 magnetostriction}}, and he found the relationship between the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 current}} through a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resistor"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 resistor}} and the heat {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dissipation"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 dissipated}}, which is also called {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joule%27s_first_law"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Joule's first law}}. His experiments about energy transformations were first published in 1843.\
\

